      { q: "How would you implement message backup to the cloud without breaking E2E encryption?", a: "Keep the backup encrypted end-to-end too: derive a 256-bit backup key client-side, either from a user-chosen password run through a memory-hard KDF (Argon2/scrypt) or a 64-digit auto-generated key, then wrap that key inside an HSM-backed key vault (WhatsApp uses a variant of HSM-based key escrow so Facebook/Meta itself can't read it, limited to a bounded number of guess attempts before the HSM locks the key). Each message/media blob is encrypted client-side with the backup key before upload to the cloud provider (iCloud/Google Drive or WhatsApp's own S3-backed store), so the server only ever sees ciphertext. Incremental backups batch new messages daily and upload media separately with content-addressed dedup so a 50GB history doesn't re-upload on every backup. Restoring requires the original device to prove key possession (password or the 64-digit key), and losing both the password and key means the backup is unrecoverable by design — that's the tradeoff for real E2E guarantees." },
      { q: "How would you scale group messages to 1000-member groups?", a: "Don't fan out at write time on the sender's device — the server-side fanout worker takes the single incoming message and pushes it onto each of the up to 1000 recipients' per-user message queues (backed by ejabberd/Erlang processes historically, or a Kafka topic per shard in a rearchitected version), so the sender does one encrypted send per recipient's device key (Signal protocol requires per-device pairwise encryption, so 1000 members with 2 devices each is ~2000 encrypted payloads generated server-side from the sender's session, not fanned out from the phone). Cap group size (1024) specifically to bound this fanout cost and the sender-side crypto work. Presence/delivery receipts are batched and rate-limited (don't send 1000 individual ack pushes) — aggregate read receipts server-side and deliver periodically. Media in group messages is uploaded once to blob storage and only a reference/key is fanned out, avoiding 1000x storage duplication." },
      { q: "How would you implement 'last seen' and online presence at 2B user scale?", a: "Presence is inherently ephemeral and high-churn, so store it in memory, not in a durable DB — each user's online/offline/last-seen timestamp lives in a sharded in-memory store (Erlang process state historically, or Redis cluster with a key per user, TTL-based) colocated with the connection-holding server so a presence update on connect/disconnect is a local write, no cross-DC round trip. Presence changes are only pushed to users who are actively viewing that contact's chat or have them open (subscribe/publish model, not broadcast to all 2B), which keeps fanout to a few hundred interested subscribers per user typically. Last-seen timestamp is persisted to Cassandra/RocksDB asynchronously and lazily for privacy-setting checks, since most reads are satisfied from the connection server's memory. Privacy rules (contacts-only, nobody) are enforced at read time by checking a small settings cache, not by restricting the write." },
      { q: "How would you handle message search across a user's entire history?", a: "Search has to be entirely client-side to preserve E2E encryption guarantees — the server never has plaintext, so there's no central search index it can build. On-device, build a local SQLite FTS5 (or similar) full-text index alongside the message store, updated incrementally as messages arrive/decrypt, indexing text content, sender, and timestamp with tokenization for the user's language. For a user with 100k+ messages this index stays a few hundred MB, acceptable for mobile storage, and queries return in tens of milliseconds since it's a local B-tree/inverted-index lookup. Media captions and forwarded text are indexed the same way; media itself (images/voice) isn't full-text searchable unless you run on-device OCR/transcription, which some clients now add as an opt-in local ML feature. Cross-device search (multi-device support) requires each device to independently rebuild its own local index from its own decrypted message store, since indexes can't sync in plaintext." }
