      { q: "How would you handle copyright detection at upload time?", a: "This is essentially Content ID: at upload, extract an audio fingerprint (e.g., a chromaprint-style spectral hash robust to pitch/tempo shifts) and a video fingerprint (frame-sampled perceptual hashes) from the new upload, then query against a reference database of fingerprints submitted by rights holders — this index needs to support fast approximate matching over tens of millions of reference works, typically an LSH (locality-sensitive hashing) index sharded by content type. A match triggers a policy lookup (the rights holder's chosen action: block, mute, monetize-and-split-revenue, or just track), applied automatically without human review for confident matches, with a review queue for low-confidence or disputed matches. This runs asynchronously post-upload (not blocking the publish flow) since fingerprinting a long video against a huge reference set can take minutes, and videos are held from public feed distribution until the scan clears for high-risk categories like music. Rights holders' reference fingerprints are re-derived periodically as fingerprinting algorithms improve, to catch previously-missed matches (retroactive scanning)." },
      { q: "How would you design the comments system at scale?", a: "Comments are a write-heavy, read-heavy tree structure — store them in a wide-column store (Bigtable/Cassandra) keyed by video_id with comment_id as a clustered column, so fetching the top-level comments for a video is a single partition range scan, and store replies as a separate row keyed by parent_comment_id to avoid deeply nested reads. Don't compute 'top comments' ranking on every read — precompute and cache a ranked comment list per video in Redis (score based on likes, recency, replies), invalidated/refreshed on new engagement events consumed off a Kafka stream, so a popular video's comment page load is a cache hit, not a live aggregation over potentially millions of comments. Like counts are approximate/eventually-consistent under high write load (a counter service that batches increments rather than doing a synchronous DB write per like) to avoid hot-row contention on viral videos. Spam/abuse filtering runs as an async pipeline (ML classifier + rule-based) before a comment is visible to anyone but the poster, to keep post latency low while still gating visibility." }
