    tradeoffs: [
      "Driver location in Redis vs DB: Redis = fast reads/writes but memory limited; DB = persistent but too slow for 1.25M updates/sec",
      "Push matching (Uber sends to specific driver) vs pull (drivers poll for requests) — push has lower latency but requires connection state",
      "Surge pricing granularity: per zip code (simple) vs per hexagon (Uber H3) — finer granularity is more accurate but more complex",
      "Consistency of trip state: MySQL (ACID for payment) vs Cassandra (eventual, but faster) — financial records need ACID",
    ],
    followUpQuestions: [
      { q: "How would you implement surge pricing in real-time?", a: "Divide the map into a hex grid (Uber uses H3, roughly 1000 sq meter cells at high resolution) and maintain a rolling supply/demand ratio per cell, updated every 30-60 seconds from a stream-processing job (Flink/Kafka Streams) consuming driver location pings and ride request events. When the demand/supply ratio in a cell crosses thresholds, a surge multiplier (1.0x-3x+ typically) is computed and written to a fast key-value store (Redis) keyed by cell ID, which the pricing service reads at request time with sub-10ms latency to quote a rider. Multipliers are smoothed/dampened (e.g., capped rate of change per minute) to avoid price whiplash and to prevent gaming by drivers going offline briefly to trigger surge. The whole pipeline needs to close the loop in under a minute end-to-end — pings in, surge computed, price quoted — since ride requests are latency-sensitive and stale surge data either overcharges riders or fails to incentivize drivers when actually needed." },
      { q: "How would you handle the case where a driver is on a trip and gets a new ride request?", a: "A driver on an active trip should simply be excluded from the dispatch candidate pool for new requests by default — the dispatch service's nearest-driver query (a geospatial index like an H3-based or quad-tree lookup in Redis/Elasticsearch) filters on driver status = 'available', and 'on trip' drivers aren't in that set at all. The exception is destination-aware batching (uberPOOL-style or 'next ride' features) where a driver nearing trip completion can be offered a new request that's en route to or near their current drop-off, computed by a separate 'upcoming availability' prediction using the driver's live ETA to destination. This requires the dispatch service to track a driver's projected-available-time and location, refreshed on every GPS ping (every 4 seconds typically), so it can proactively match a soon-to-be-free driver instead of only reacting to 'available' status changes, cutting idle time between trips." },
      { q: "How would you design the ETA prediction system?", a: "Don't rely on static road-speed averages — feed a machine-learned model (Uber's actual system, DeepETA/similar, uses a transformer-style or gradient-boosted model) real-time features: current road segment speeds aggregated from live GPS traces of all cars on that road in the last few minutes, historical time-of-day/day-of-week patterns, weather, and known events (accidents, closures) ingested from a separate incident feed. Precompute a road graph with segment-level speed estimates refreshed every 1-2 minutes via a streaming aggregation job (Flink consuming GPS pings from millions of active trips), stored in a graph-friendly store, then run a routing algorithm (Uber's own, similar to a modified Dijkstra/A* over the weighted graph) to get base travel time, and apply the ML correction model on top for the final ETA. Model is retrained continuously on actual-vs-predicted arrival time as ground truth, with online monitoring for drift, since traffic patterns shift with construction/events and a stale model quickly loses accuracy — production targets are typically within 10-15% of actual arrival time for the median trip." },
      { q: "How would you detect and prevent fraudulent trips?", a: "Run a real-time fraud-scoring service in the trip pipeline that flags anomalies as events stream in (Kafka topic per trip lifecycle event): GPS spoofing detection (comparing device GPS against cell-tower/WiFi triangulation, or looking for impossible speed jumps), fake-trip patterns (driver and rider accounts colluding, detected via graph analysis linking device IDs, payment methods, and frequent same-pair pairings), and route-manipulation (comparing actual GPS trace against the expected route/distance for the fare charged). A gradient-boosted or graph neural network model scores each completed trip using these signals plus account history (account age, prior flags, device fingerprint reuse across accounts) within seconds of trip completion, and high-risk trips get held from automatic payout/rating pending review rather than blocking in real time (fraud review is usually post-hoc, not a blocker to picking up a rider, since false positives there hurt legitimate drivers badly). Device fingerprinting and a shared graph database of known-fraud device/payment clusters lets new fraudulent accounts get caught fast even before they complete their first trip, since they often reuse hardware or payment instruments from previously banned accounts." }
    ],
    redFlags: [
      "Storing driver locations in a relational DB and running geospatial queries — will not scale",
      "No real-time location streaming (WebSocket) for riders to track driver",
      "Not addressing the 1.25M location updates/sec ingestion problem",
      "Single server/region design for a globally distributed, latency-sensitive service",
    ],
