      { q: "How would you design the merchant payout system?", a: "Maintain a merchant balance ledger (double-entry, append-only) that accumulates net-of-fee transaction credits in near real time as charges settle, then run a payout scheduler (daily/weekly/instant tiers) that batches eligible balance into a payout run per merchant, holding a rolling reserve (e.g., 5-10% held for 7 days) to cover chargebacks and refunds. Payouts execute via ACH/wire/local rails (e.g., Stripe uses a partner bank + NACHA files for ACH in the US), with each payout getting an idempotent batch ID so a retry after a network failure doesn't double-pay. Reconciliation runs nightly against bank statements (via SFTP/API from the payout bank) to catch returned/failed ACH transactions (R01 insufficient funds, etc.) and automatically reverse the merchant's ledger balance. For instant payouts, integrate with debit-network push-to-card (Visa Direct/Mastercard Send) which settles in minutes but costs more, funded from a pre-funded settlement account so you're not waiting on the slower ACH cycle." }
