    followUpQuestions: [
      { q: "How would you implement rate limiting without Redis (purely in memory per server)?", a: "Each server keeps a local sliding-window or token-bucket counter per key (user/API key) in an in-process concurrent map (e.g., a striped ConcurrentHashMap in Java or sync.Map in Go) with a background goroutine/thread that decays or resets buckets on their window boundary, giving sub-microsecond check latency since there's no network hop. The obvious problem is that behind a load balancer with N servers, each server only sees 1/N of a client's traffic, so a global limit of 1000 req/min effectively becomes 1000*N req/min if traffic isn't sticky. You mitigate this either by using consistent-hash-based routing at the load balancer (route by API key so all of a client's requests land on the same server, making the local counter authoritative) or by accepting the limit is approximate and setting the per-node threshold to limit/N with periodic gossip between nodes (lightweight UDP broadcast of local counts every 1-2s) to true up estimates. This trades strict accuracy for zero external dependency and near-zero latency, appropriate when being under-strict occasionally (allowing some burst) is acceptable." },
      { q: "How would you handle rate limits that span multiple microservices?", a: "Centralize the rate-limit decision behind a single shared service (or Redis cluster with Lua scripts implementing atomic sliding-window-counter or GCRA/leaky-bucket logic) that every microservice calls through a common client library or a sidecar (Envoy's rate limit filter talking to a gRPC rate-limit service), so the limit is enforced once per logical request regardless of how many internal services that request touches. Push the enforcement point as close to the edge as possible (API gateway) for the outer request-level limit, and use the shared Redis-backed service for any secondary limits enforced deeper in the call graph, tagging the rate-limit key with a consistent identifier (API key or user ID) propagated via a request header across service boundaries. At scale, a Redis Cluster sharded by key hash handles this centrally with sub-millisecond latency (colocated in the same region/AZ as the calling services), and you'd use Envoy's rate limit filter's local caching to avoid a network round-trip on every single request when the client is well under quota." },
      { q: "How would you give different rate limits to different API key tiers (free/pro/enterprise)?", a: "Store tier-to-limit mappings in a config table (Postgres or a config service) keyed by plan name (free: 100 req/min, pro: 10k req/min, enterprise: custom per-account overrides), cached in-memory on each rate-limiter node with a short TTL (30-60s) or invalidated via a pub/sub event when a plan changes, so a plan upgrade takes effect within seconds without a redeploy. At request time, resolve the API key to its account and tier (cached in Redis alongside the counter, e.g., a hash `ratelimit:{key}` storing both the tier and the current window count) so tier lookup and limit check happen in the same round trip. Use token-bucket rather than fixed-window for paid tiers so enterprise customers get burst capacity (e.g., bucket capacity 2x the steady rate) which better matches bursty real-world API usage patterns than a hard per-minute wall. For enterprise accounts with custom SLAs, allow per-account overrides layered on top of the tier default, checked first, falling back to the tier's default limit." }
    ],
