      { q: "How would you implement end-to-end encrypted DMs?", a: "Use the Signal/Double Ratchet protocol: each client generates an identity key pair plus signed prekeys and one-time prekeys, uploads the public bundle to a key server, and the sender does an X3DH handshake to derive a shared secret before any message is sent, so Discord's servers only ever relay ciphertext blobs. Each message uses a per-message key derived via the ratchet (HKDF over the chain key), giving forward secrecy even if a device key is later compromised. Store ciphertext plus metadata (sender, timestamp, recipient) in Cassandra keyed by channel_id/message_id for fanout, but never store plaintext or keys server-side. Multi-device support requires per-device sessions (fan out to each of a user's registered device keys) which is the hard part operationally — Signal handles this with sender keys for groups but 1:1 device fanout for DMs. Key rotation and safety-number verification UI let users detect MITM attempts." },
      { q: "How would you handle message edits and deletes (audit trail)?", a: "Never mutate the original row: store messages in Cassandra partitioned by channel_id with message_id (Snowflake, time-sortable) as clustering key, and writes for edits/deletes go into a separate message_revisions table keyed by (message_id, revision_ts) storing a diff or full snapshot plus editor_id. The 'live' message view is a materialized read that takes the latest revision, so reads stay O(1) via a pointer/version column on the primary row rather than scanning revisions. Deletes are soft — set deleted_at and tombstone the content after a retention window (e.g., 30 days) for moderation/legal holds, then a background job hard-deletes past that window to bound storage. Audit log entries (who edited/deleted, when, old content hash) are also streamed to Kafka and sink into a separate moderation datastore so trust & safety can query history without touching the hot path. Fan-out to connected clients over the gateway websocket sends only the edit/delete event with new content, not the full history." },
      { q: "How would you scale voice channels to 10K simultaneous listeners (podcast mode)?", a: "Switch from full mesh/SFU-per-speaker to a broadcast topology: a small number of active speakers (say 1-10) send audio via WebRTC to an SFU cluster, which transcodes/mixes into a single Opus stream and fans it out through a CDN-like relay tree (regional media relays, similar to Discord's actual 'Stage' voice architecture) rather than each SFU node holding 10K direct WebRTC connections. Listeners join in receive-only mode and get placed on the nearest edge relay (colocated with Discord's existing voice server regions), so a single origin SFU only pushes N regional streams, not 10K individual streams — this is a fanout tree, same idea as HLS edge fanout. Use RTP simulcast/redundancy but skip per-listener adaptive bitrate complexity since it's audio-only (mono Opus at 64kbps is cheap, 10K listeners at 64kbps is ~640Mbps aggregate which the tree structure divides across edges). Speaker-side stays low latency (~100-200ms) via direct SFU; listener-side can tolerate 1-2s extra buffering for stability, which is what makes the tree fanout feasible without every node maintaining thousands of live WebRTC sessions." }
