      { q: "How would you handle 50K participant webinars?", a: "50K participants can't all be WebRTC peers or even SFU subscribers to a live mixed stream cost-effectively, so webinars split roles: a handful of panelists (up to ~100) connect via real SFU/WebRTC for interactive audio/video, and everyone else is a view-only attendee who receives a server-side composited stream via HLS/low-latency HLS or a proprietary UDP-based fanout through Zoom's CDN edge network. The mixing server composites panelist video into a single output feed (a virtual 'broadcast'), transcodes to a few bitrate rungs, and pushes to edge PoPs which fan out to attendees — this converts an O(N) unicast problem into O(edge nodes) origin load, with each edge serving thousands of attendees from cache. Accept 2-5s of glass-to-glass latency for attendees (chat/reactions can still feel live) in exchange for scale; interactive elements (Q&A, polls, hand-raise) go through a separate low-throughput control-plane channel (WebSocket + Kafka) since those are low-frequency events, not the video path. Capacity plan for the CDN egress bandwidth as the dominant cost: 50K viewers at even 500kbps average is 25Gbps aggregate, so multi-CDN with regional PoPs is essential to keep last-mile latency and cost sane." },
      { q: "How would you design the hand-raise and speaker queue features?", a: "This is a small-scale, low-latency control-plane problem, not a media problem: hand-raise events go over the existing signaling WebSocket connection to a per-meeting coordinator service (in-memory state, backed by Redis for the meeting's queue so any host-app instance can serve reconnects), appended as a FIFO ordered list keyed by meeting_id with timestamp for ordering. The host client subscribes to queue-change events pushed via the same WebSocket fanout used for meeting state (participant list, mute state), so no polling is needed and updates land in under 200ms. State transitions (raise -> host acknowledges -> promote to speaker -> lower hand) are modeled as an explicit state machine per participant, persisted in Redis with a TTL tied to meeting lifetime so a crashed coordinator instance can be replaced and rehydrate queue state without losing data. Given queue sizes are typically dozens not thousands, this doesn't need Kafka or a heavy queue system — Redis lists/sorted-sets keyed per meeting plus the existing meeting WebSocket fanout channel is sufficient and keeps operational complexity low." }
