      { q: "How would you implement real-time collaborative editing (Google Docs style) in Dropbox?", a: "This needs a fundamentally different model than Dropbox's file-sync-and-diff approach: use Operational Transformation (OT) or CRDTs (like Yjs/Automerge) so concurrent edits from multiple clients merge deterministically without locking. Each edit is an operation (insert/delete at position with metadata) broadcast through a low-latency WebSocket connection to a central sequencing server per document, which assigns a total order and transforms/rebases concurrent ops against each other (OT) or lets a CRDT's merge function resolve conflicts commutatively without a central sequencer at all — Automerge/Yjs favor CRDTs specifically because they avoid the complexity of OT's transform functions and work offline-first, which matters for a Dropbox-style product where clients frequently disconnect. Persist the operation log (not just snapshots) to allow replay/undo and periodically checkpoint a full document snapshot to object storage (S3-like) so reload doesn't require replaying the entire history. This collaborative-doc path runs alongside, not instead of, Dropbox's existing block-based file sync (used for binary files and the periodic snapshot artifact itself) — the two systems would need to interoperate so a live-edited doc still shows up as a synced file in the file tree once checkpointed." },
      { q: "How would you handle very large files (100GB video files)?", a: "Split the file into fixed-size chunks (4-8MB, similar to Dropbox's actual block-based storage) so we only upload/re-upload changed blocks rather than the whole file. Each chunk is content-addressed via SHA-256, deduplicated across users, and uploaded in parallel over multiple TCP connections to S3-compatible object storage using multipart upload APIs. For a 100GB file at 8MB chunks that's ~12,500 blocks; we track upload progress per-block in a metadata DB (Cassandra) so a network drop only requires resuming the missing chunks, not restarting. On the client, we throttle concurrent uploads (e.g., 4-8 parallel streams) and use resumable multipart with ETags to verify integrity, and background/idle-priority scheduling so it doesn't saturate the user's bandwidth." },
      { q: "How would you implement selective sync (only sync specific folders)?", a: "Maintain a client-side sync manifest (a local SQLite DB) that marks each folder/file node with a sync state: synced, placeholder (metadata-only), or excluded. When a user deselects a folder, the client walks the local tree, deletes local blocks but keeps a lightweight placeholder/stub with metadata (name, size, modified date) so it still appears in Explorer/Finder as an online-only file. The server's file-system tree (stored as a versioned Merkle-like structure, one row per node with parent pointers) is unaffected — selective sync is purely a client-side filter applied on top of the full account tree the server tracks. On re-selection, the client diffs its manifest against the server's tree via a delta API (like a changelist since last cursor) and pulls only the blocks needed, avoiding a full re-scan." }
